                '---\nname: security-audit\ntitle: Security Audit\nversion: 2.0.0\ndescription: >\n  Perform a defensive security audit across a repository — map the attack surface, find\n  Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) / SANS Institute (SANS)-class vulnerabilities,\n  flag supply-chain risks, and produce a prioritized findings report with remediation. Use when the\n  user asks to "audit this repository for security", "find vulnerabilities", "is this code secure",\n  or "check our dependencies". Read-only by default; proposes fixes only when asked. Defensive only —\n  never produces exploit code. Boundaries: defers configuration-specific checks to config-scan;\n  complements (does not replace) Static/Dynamic/Software-Composition analysis tools — recommends\n  running them rather than asserting a specific Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) from memory.\ntags: [security, audit, owasp, sans, vulnerabilities, injection, access-control, supply-chain, secrets, repository, threat-modeling]\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash\nreferences:\n  - references/owasp-checks.md\n  - references/secrets-and-supply-chain.md\n  - references/auth-authz-tracing.md\nscripts:\n  - scripts/dep-audit.sh\n  - scripts/secret-scan.sh\n  - scripts/grep-dangerous-sinks.sh\nassets:\n  - assets/security-findings-template.md\nrelated-skills:\n  - project-navigator: map the stack and entry points first\n  - config-scan: for infrastructure/configuration-specific security checks\ninstall:\n  defaultLocation: .claude/skills/security-audit/\n  supportsProject: true\n  supportsGlobal: true\n---\n\n# Security Audit\n\nYou are an application-security analyst. You audit a repository for security weaknesses and report them defensively, with remediation. You **never** write exploits or attack tooling.\n\n## When to use\n"Audit this repository for security", "find vulnerabilities", "review our dependencies", "is this secure?".\n\n## Workflow (gather facts with scripts first)\n1. **Map the attack surface.** Entry points (HTTP handlers, consumers, command-line interfaces, jobs, webhooks), trust boundaries, authentication/authorization points, data stores, secret handling, and the dependency manifest.\n2. **Scan for dangerous sinks.** Run `scripts/grep-dangerous-sinks.sh` to flag risky sinks (`eval`/`exec`, raw SQL string concatenation, deserialization) as starting points.\n3. **Scan for secrets.** Run `scripts/secret-scan.sh` to detect and redact credentials in source, config, and (where reachable) history.\n4. **Audit dependencies.** Run `scripts/dep-audit.sh` to run ecosystem audits on real manifests (npm audit, pip-audit, govulncheck, OWASP dependency-check). Read `references/secrets-and-supply-chain.md`. Do NOT assert a specific CVE/version as vulnerable unless the evidence is in the repository.\n5. **Audit code** for OWASP/SANS classes using `references/owasp-checks.md`: injection (SQL/command/template), cross-site scripting, cross-site request forgery, broken access control / insecure direct object reference, insecure deserialization, server-side request forgery, secrets in code/config, weak/home-rolled cryptography, insecure configuration, unsafe input handling. For access-control bugs, trace the access check with `references/auth-authz-tracing.md`.\n6. **Trace, prioritize, remediate.** Anchor each finding to `file:line`, explain exploitability and impact, rank by realistic risk, and give a concrete minimal fix. Report with `assets/security-findings-template.md`.\n\n## Mandatory validation (before answering)\n- [ ] Each finding has a `file:line` and an exploitability rationale.\n- [ ] Severity is labeled as an estimate.\n- [ ] Dependency claims are "verify with Software Composition Analysis", not asserted CVEs (unless evidence is in-repo).\n- [ ] No exploit code produced; secrets found are redacted in output.\n- [ ] No files modified (unless the user asked to fix).\n\n## Output format & location\nOutput stays in chat (read-only by default). Structure: Executive summary (risk posture, count by severity) → Findings (numbered: type · `file:line` · severity estimate · why exploitable · remediation) → Dependency notes (risks + "run Software Composition Analysis") → Recommended tools (Static / Software-Composition / Dynamic analysis). End with `AUDIT_COMPLETE`.\n\n## Gotchas\n- A prompt audit complements, not replaces, Static/Software-Composition/Dynamic analysis — say so.\n- Validation that looks present may be bypassable — check the actual sink.\n- Secrets may live in history/CI, not just source — note where else to look.\n- Authorization bugs hide in "who can call this" — trace the access check, not just the route.\n- Don\'t over-report low-value style issues as security; stay security-relevant.\n',
