                '<!--\n  SECURITY FINDINGS REPORT TEMPLATE\n  Defensive only. Report detection + remediation. Never include exploit payloads.\n  Fill every bracketed [ ... ] placeholder. Delete rows/sections that do not apply.\n  Keep output in chat unless the user asked for a file.\n\n  SEVERITY-ESTIMATE LEGEND (all severities are ESTIMATES, not certified ratings):\n    Critical — directly exploitable, high impact (e.g. unauth remote code execution,\n               trivial account takeover, secret granting broad access committed in source).\n    High     — exploitable with realistic preconditions and serious impact (e.g. IDOR exposing\n               other users\' data, SQL injection on an authenticated endpoint).\n    Medium   — exploitable under specific conditions or with limited impact.\n    Low      — weakness with minor or hard-to-reach impact.\n    Info     — hardening opportunity / not directly exploitable.\n\n  FILLING GUIDANCE:\n    - Anchor every finding to file:line and explain WHY it is exploitable (attacker-controlled\n      input reaching the sink), not just that a pattern matched.\n    - Label severity as an estimate; do not present it as an authoritative score.\n    - For dependencies, say "verify with Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"; do not assert a\n      specific CVE/version from memory unless the evidence is in the repository.\n    - Redact any secret discovered; never reproduce a raw credential.\n-->\n\n# Security Audit Report\n\n> Scope: [repository / path audited]\n> Date: [YYYY-MM-DD]\n> Mode: read-only (no files modified) | [or] fix-proposing (user requested remediation edits)\n> Note: This prompt-based audit COMPLEMENTS — it does not replace — Static Application Security\n> Testing (SAST), Software Composition Analysis (SCA), and Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST).\n\n## Executive summary\n\n**Risk posture:** [1–3 sentences on overall security state and the most material risks.]\n\n**Count by severity (estimates):**\n\n| Severity | Count |\n|----------|-------|\n| Critical | [n]   |\n| High     | [n]   |\n| Medium   | [n]   |\n| Low      | [n]   |\n| Info     | [n]   |\n\n**Attack surface noted:** [entry points, trust boundaries, auth points, data stores reviewed.]\n\n## Findings\n\n<!-- One block per finding. Number sequentially. Order by severity (Critical first). -->\n\n### [1] [vulnerability class, e.g. A03 Injection — SQL] [short title]\n- **Location:** `[path/to/file.ext:line]`\n- **Severity (estimate):** [Critical | High | Medium | Low | Info]\n- **Why exploitable:** [What input is attacker-controlled and how it reaches this sink; why the\n  control is missing or bypassable. Defensive description only — no payload.]\n- **Impact:** [What an attacker could achieve — data exposure, account takeover, code execution, etc.]\n- **Remediation:** [Concrete minimal fix — e.g. use a parameterized query / scope the lookup to\n  current_user / enable TLS verification. Reference the safe pattern.]\n\n### [2] [class] [title]\n- **Location:** `[file:line]`\n- **Severity (estimate):** [ ... ]\n- **Why exploitable:** [ ... ]\n- **Impact:** [ ... ]\n- **Remediation:** [ ... ]\n\n<!-- Add more findings as needed, continuing the numbering. -->\n\n## Dependency notes\n\n[Summarize manifest/lockfile hygiene and any supply-chain risk signals observed: unpinned ranges,\nmissing lockfile/integrity hashes, lookalike/abandoned packages, lifecycle scripts, dependency\nconfusion. Report tool output from dep-audit.sh if available.]\n\n> **Verify with Software Composition Analysis (SCA).** Do not treat the above as authoritative CVE\n> findings unless a tool reported them or the evidence is in-repo. Pin versions, commit lockfiles,\n> and run SCA in continuous integration.\n\n## Recommended tools\n\n- **Static Application Security Testing (SAST):** [recommend running a SAST tool on this codebase\n  to catch code-level issues at scale.]\n- **Software Composition Analysis (SCA):** [recommend SCA / a Software Bill of Materials process to\n  authoritatively map dependency vulnerabilities.]\n- **Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST):** [recommend DAST against a running instance to\n  catch runtime/configuration issues this static review cannot see.]\n\n<!--\n  Secrets reminder: secrets may also live in git history, CI variables, or Dockerfile ARG/ENV.\n  A committed secret should be rotated, not just deleted. Redact all secret values above.\n-->\n\nAUDIT_COMPLETE\n',
